Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans not mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought on this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the area of Kavarna and Balcik also.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, the shops and office spaces promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shore of the Black Sea and in the most reputable ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers fall into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>50 to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>100 thousand, or old decayed houses, at a price ranging from <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>5 to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 thousand, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, the proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving a capital gain in the medium or long term.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly increasing as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, at the moment, it does not want to discuss exact figures, while it is ready to sign an agreement on reducing, until 2020, greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from the 1990 level.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit, apart from emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors likely under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac es Profit (Market and Profit) said.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to remain a flagship in the overall efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020, regardless of the successful signing of the ‘After 2012 Agreement’, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to take on appropriate commitments and capacities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol signatory countries had aimed at a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time made the commitment on 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the Nobel agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, commitments to reduce below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the new scientific body whose international report has been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided which, according to the scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
The British army units are communicating, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units intervening in Afghanistan upload video footage on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Soldiers of the air force have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this way and their "chain" was watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered under the name "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and broadcasts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the Air Force's original objective, the videos were put on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
Propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, defence consultant Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the validity of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos had already been streamed on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real mission, but the British army is keen to upload these videos only recently.
The Americans do the recruiting a little differently by using the shooting game America's Army downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
