The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of the United Kingdom, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be placed on the money markets through auctions.
The banks will have to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are ready to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even mitigate the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to customers.
"Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still expecting billions more losses.
“If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is because they have to really understand what can still happen,” says ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“I hear the situation is really bad,” he added.
The central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
Central banks made this choice after they failed to lower the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks still feared mutual borrowing, even though the U.S., Canadian, and British central banks repeatedly lowered interest rates in the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further fall in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
