Integration of Slovak students in British schools is going badly
The number of children from Eastern European countries in British schools is increasing, causing concern among the remaining children about the development of local education.
For the time being, the integration of Eastern Europeans faces a number of obstacles.
British schools even see cases where conflicts between immigrants and descendants of the original inhabitants turn into violence.
The case of North Kent, where conflicts between Slovak residents and Slovak immigrants are beginning to intensify, illustrates the problem of the integration of children from Eastern Europe.
Disputes, chicanes and quarrels between students have been transposed into the relationship between the parents.
The situation has gone so far that police in Chatham have arrested a Slovak woman who was beating a ten-year-old student with an iron bar.
The culprit defends herself by claiming that the boy had insulted him with racist remarks.
Police also had to intervene following the attack on a Slovak immigrant by two teenage girls.
The girls allegedly addressed racist remarks to the man and threw stones at him.
“As we were coming home, a young man climbed on the bus stop and started spitting on us.
When I told him to stop, he responded with apples and pears and then he discovered his buttocks," described another unpleasant adventure a mother of Slovak students.
Complaints are made by both parties.
One of the remaining ones went so far as to call conflicts with immigrants a struggle for survival.
The cases mentioned above testify that the atmosphere in British schools between natives and immigrants is beginning to be tense.
Seventy thousand Slovaks who came to find work are registered in Great Britain.
And about 30,000 Slovak students attend British schools.
Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can happen if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
There is only one island on which you will find much more and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the deposit and place of transhipment of the treasures that the Spanish had stolen and that they transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920s.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the heads of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the USA (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50s of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and, in Cojímar, he had his yacht.
Show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your own autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita de la Habana.
In the bar of the hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigoulis and fiats once imported have already for a long time, in such a salty and humid climate, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is significantly decrepit, nowhere else in the surroundings are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if necessary, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane was re-entered from the plantations extended into the sweets on a narrow track by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how small locomotives can be seen in motion whose contemporaries are not elsewhere only in museums.
Where to direct your steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the best known places.
So there is no need to write long about Varadero or Havana.
Not to mention that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and anyone who loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows on limestone soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons and rocks rise in candlelight from the bottom of the valley, and, from the fertile earth that has been taken into their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense plant carpet.
The valley is probably the place where the highest quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can experience the final form of this product if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Someone may also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was shot.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought it glory and wealth.
The richness was embodied in the beauty and the city-vitrine character of this small city.
Koloniální <0xC5><0xA1>pan<0xC4><0x9B>lská architektura,v<0xC3><0xBD>razn<0xC4><0x9B> ovlivn<0xC4><0x9B>ná pozd<0xC4><0x9B>j<0xC5><0xA1>ími francouzsk<0xC3><0xBD>mi osadníky, <0xC4><0x8D>ty<0xC5><0x99>i staletí tém<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0x99> nezm<0xC4><0x9B>nila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is a place so remote that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay on the sidelines.
Nothing was built, and that is why nothing was demolished either, everyone was content to have a roof over their head.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is also worth going to see interesting places in the surroundings, such as Playa Ancón beach or the Sucreries valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música which comes to life after sunset and where the music deafens only in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this town located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads there.
The two roads that lead there from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross a landscape almost without traces of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed the Eastern Rock of Cuba, thanks to its unspoilt landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (actually, it was born about a hundred years after the voyage of Columbus) and from the hill where stands the old castle and the current hotel El Castillo, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain range, Sow Bay and Isla de Pinos Island, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of Cuba's patron saint Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of the ancient slaves, about all this one could fill up a number of pages.
But, as they say, it’s better to see it once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, US says
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, influences the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the years to come.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh in Scotland the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
Alongside the growing protest from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and allied coordination.
While the U.S. this week called through Defense Minister Robert Gates for NATO troops to step up activity, Britain prioritizes strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and intensifying development aid.
"The evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the inhabitants to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
Afghan insurgent activity is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 percent from last year, to 60 percent in the southern province of Helmand.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, almost a quarter of them in the south.
Now, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit and in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Concretely, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we would need, and that's not enough," De Hoop told Reuters at the end of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is Passive
In recent months, there have also been conflicts among the countries involved over whether all allies are doing their utmost in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat demands they are subject to are not as rigorous as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate," Gates said.
British tabloid Sun this week called German soldiers lazy.
“Uncovered lazy Afghans: Germans play, while ours fight,” Sun wrote in a document supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper Bild went on to counterattack by publishing a photo of a British troop during a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
State debt will rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech.
Total debt rose to 842.7 billion kroner at the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
Thanks to better-than-expected state budget savings, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion kroner.
During the nine months of this year, it increased by 40.2 billion kroner.
However, as of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on the state debt as of the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has indebted more than 111 billion kroner.
“For now, it appears that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could cross the border by a trillion kroner in 2009 alone.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion kroner,” said Patria Finance analyst David Marek for iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor’s forecast is similar: “One could surpass the trillion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it turns out that the political situation is changing, that policies are willing to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I’m not expecting this change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated essentially by the accumulation of deficits of the state budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bonds, annuity bonds, direct loans or, for example, by loans from the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the state has increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state's external debt has so far increased this year from 1.7 billion kronor to 123.3 billion kronor.
The so-called negotiable state debt reached at the end of September 803.3 billion kroner and as of June it decreased by 13.7 billion kroner.
The average debt owed by the State was 6.5 years.
"Total debt has increased year-on-year from the first to the third half by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a far too high figure.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt grows, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be room to negotiate when pension reform comes," Pikora said.
Better than expected
It follows from the government's debt financing and management strategy for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution in the savings of the state budget, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The sum consists essentially of the deficit of the state budget which will obviously reach 76 billion kroner this year, instead of the 91.3 billion kroner initially planned.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion kroner, the 10 billion reserve for the payment of pensions, the financing of government annuity bonds for 43 billion kroner and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion kroner.
She was in court today in Khartoum for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting students from 6 to 7 years old give the name of Mohammed to a teddy bear while any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punished with a lash.
The 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested Sunday at her home and charged with assault on Islam and sedition, under Article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints by parents of pupils to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asked her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a class vote, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their favorite first name.
Muhammad is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the picture of the bear followed by the caption "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself had no label with that name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name", according to him it was only an "innocent mistake".
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very caring towards her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Is it possible to give it to a toy?
This is of course a question of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on Wednesday on the future status of the province, during the last session of negotiations in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
The Serbs and Albanians of Kosovo concluded Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, a sixth and final session of discussions without being able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties were not able to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region was “at stake,” his U.S. counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to honor their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
“We do not foresee violence in the immediate future but we are entering a very difficult period,” he added, noting that “obvious tensions exist.”
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90 percent Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final round of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new UN mediation last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council from granting independence to Kosovo, insist that negotiations continue beyond that deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Botshan-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners believe that independence under EU supervision is the only viable solution.
Pristina is ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced in the hotel in Baden where these "negotiations of the last chance" were taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations.”
‘Domino effect’
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still possible, warning Kosovo's Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
In particular, Belgrade says it fears a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
“For Serbia,” he said, “this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.”
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto.
“Kosovo’s parliament will have the last word”
“Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia,” Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
