It took astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates on the International Space Station (ISS) more than seven hours of work in space to make the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, essential to the station's continued scientific activities.
A risky outing that has accumulated records due to its duration, its distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, the tools “do-it-yourself” by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem appeared on Tuesday when astronauts unloaded the Discovery module Harmony, a large cylindrical piece that will soon host European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of dock for modules-laboratories.
But we need to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move a 17.5-tonne solar panel power generation module, already present on the ISS, to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the module's solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged for nearly a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was halted so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to perform a control exit of the Discovery shuttle and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go snail at the end of the 30 meters long remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skillful, it has a very developed torso and long arms.
At 46, this doctor of training was therefore in charge of “operating” the “injured” solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the faulty cable and installed some sort of “slats” on the damaged area.
He was aided by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey rod wrapped in insulation to prevent electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and crafted by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before taking inventory of his tools and returning to the interior of the station.
