A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives in Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only searchable for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his assignees.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States having been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research "including on the movement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of this archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the opening of these nominative documents to the public, owing to the sensitivity of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
