The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine sounds the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas ferments between Ukraine and Russia, thus increasing the risks of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are transported through pipelines, and each pipeline is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two had caused a decrease in supplies to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, a Russian-owned monopoly company supplying the gas, tried in vain to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as planned since it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would mean for Ukraine, a 40% increase in the costs of imports from Gazprom.
"It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the conversations, reminding that we are a country through which most gas transits," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters news agency.
“The fluctuations in gas costs would probably be related to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.”
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused in January 2006 the interruption of supplies of Gazprom destined for Ukraine.
This resulted in falling exports to Western Europe, consequently raising prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supplies.
Russia has the largest gas stocks, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
The health ministry “must control its foreign employees.”
The Scottish Ministry of Health needs to improve the checks to be carried out on its extra-community employees to check if they have criminal precedents, the control committee said.
The warning from the Auditor General, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was involved in the June Glasgow airport attack.
Mr. Black also expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health has no specific data on the number of overseas employees it employs.
His report nonetheless highlighted other decisive controls, correctly carried out on a sample of employees from five health authorities.
The Auditor General did checks on extra-community personnel following the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Addullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing his jeep into the gates of the main terminal.
He was one of three doctors who were filmed at the Old Bailey in October, suspected of involvement in various car blast attempts in the UK.
The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas personnel, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experience, and work permits for the United Kingdom.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses the Scottish Disclosure to carry out previous criminal checks, the agency has no right to obtain such information outside of Britain.
Among the many warnings, the report of the Auditor General now states that committees are required to confront the Criminal Records Review Office, thus allowing employers to undertake checks on various countries.
"Although we have found that some personnel information has been verified, this is not done every time," the report said.
Mr. Black said that the Scottish Ministry of Health performs most of the pre-employment checks it would do itself, but he also added: "our report highlights aspects where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on some overseas staff is available to health services.
Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was “extremely unlikely” that pre-employment checks could identify employees likely to commit future terrorist acts.
He said "the report suggests that the pre-employment checks currently carried out are working well in the Scottish health system and that it is not certain that these warnings will bring any added value."
Scottish health authorities said they employed 1,161 people from overseas, mostly doctors and nurses.
But the Auditor General stressed that these figures certainly need to be revised upwards, in part because of problems with the identification of permanent contract staff who may or may not choose to remain in our country.
The investigation has shown that the current control procedures of the health authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian, are quite adequate.
These checks are carried out on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and system of pre-employment controls for overseas health service personnel.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was excited to do this work following the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
