Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and windstorms at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have been assuming that there are flashes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today provided the proof - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightning bolts on Venus erupt at a height of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have brought life to Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be very few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about one hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the infernal twin of Earth, but she remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which resembles Earth so much in mass and dimensions, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venus research, as no probe was on its way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the researchers' opinion, the most recent research findings that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles do not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than initially assumed.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the already known whirlwinds of wind at the north pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
Of both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
