Musharraf reigns as a civilian for the first time.
A day after his retirement as head of the armies, Pakistani powerman Musharraf was sworn in as president.
Thus ends eight years of military rule.
Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf was sworn in on Thursday for a new five-year term.
Pakistani television broadcast the ceremony live at the presidential palace in the capital Islamabad.
Musharraf vowed to respect the Constitution and act for the welfare of the nation.
On Wednesday, he handed over his position as commander of the armies to his confidant Ashfaq Kiyani and thus bowed to international pressure, including that of the United States.
Eight years after his seizure of power by a bloodless coup, the former general now reigns for the first time as head of civil status.
By withdrawing from the post of Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces, Musharraf had fulfilled the main requirement of the opposition and the West.
Another central requirement is the end of the state of emergency that Musharraf decreed on November 3.
Already shortly after his inauguration Musharraf will suspend the state of emergency, according to Attorney General Malik Muhammad Qayyum, and thus fulfill another requirement of the West.
The country's Supreme Court, which Musharraf had occupied after the state of emergency was instituted with lawyers from his ranks, dismissed last week all appeals against the controversial re-election of the head of state on Oct. 6.
