Von Beust picks up the criticism for the cancellation of the Olympics.
The mayor's retreat from Hamburg's bid for the Summer Olympics has met with virulent criticism in politics and the economy.
Many want to keep fighting for the Games by the water.
But Von Beust calls for realism in the appreciation of opportunity.
The principal director of the Hamburg Chamber of Commerce, Hans-Jörg Schmidt-Trenz, described the abandonment on Wednesday as "bad for the local economy".
In recent times, no other project has deployed as much motivational force in the city as the idea of the Olympics.
"Without this objective, the political and sporting momentum could not have been maintained in the same measures."
Schmidt-Trenz called on the Senate not to bury the project, but to find a new, longer-term starting point, "which takes as a starting point another modified agenda."
Mayor Ole von Beust remained on Wednesday at his previous statements, according to which the Olympic ambitions of Hamburg were unrealistic at least until the year 2028.
"It is not Hamburg that decides on a bid for the Olympics, but the German Federation of Olympic Sports," Von Beust told WELT ONLINE.
It refers to the expected decision of the Sports Federation in early December, regarding the candidacy of Munich for the 2018 Winter Games.
This preference means for us, that in the time frame we had planned until 2028 so far, we will have no chance.”
