These aren't Warhol's crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden crate, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" circulated a few months ago in doubt the authenticity of Andy Warhol's "Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968", the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten - one of the hundreds of Briy's great gifts on the market in 1995.
Ancient history is entangled, a bewildering chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden cases, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden crates produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time are now talking about about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as original licensed Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum falsely claimed later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later have ceded to him.
In truth, the 105 cases of Hultén were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that date, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies dating from the year 1990 reveals on the contrary that the paint was directly applied without a layer of background on the laminate panels, using a roll of paint - moreover it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection.
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap cases.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
The Rebel Soldiers of Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers gave up, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not be held accountable for any bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to the government had stormed the hotel shortly before using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched for hours in the building.
About half of them were in court on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - including Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to watch over them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The troops loyal to the government closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The Chair convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' action.
“People have had enough,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
Gen. Danilo Lim, who pre-commanded the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila had already been the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke down almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
